  "prompt": "What are some AngularJS interview questions?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a breakdown of AngularJS interview questions, categorized by topic and difficulty, along with explanations and potential answers.  This should give you a comprehensive idea of what to expect.\n\n**I. Fundamentals & Core Concepts**\n\n*   **What is AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:** AngularJS is a JavaScript-based open-source front-end web framework mainly maintained by Google. It aims to simplify the development and testing of single-page applications (SPAs) by providing a structured framework. It uses the Model-View-Controller (MVC) architectural pattern.\n*   **What are the key features of AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **Two-way data binding:**  Changes in the model automatically update the view, and vice versa.\n        *   **MVC Architecture:** Provides a structured way to organize code.\n        *   **Directives:** Allow you to extend HTML with custom attributes and elements, creating reusable components.\n        *   **Filters:** Format data for display (e.g., dates, currency).\n        *   **Services:** Reusable business logic that can be injected into controllers, directives, and other services.\n        *   **Dependency Injection (DI):** Simplifies testing and allows for loose coupling.\n        *   **Routing:** Enables navigation within a single-page application.\n        *   **Templating:**  Uses HTML templates to create dynamic views.\n        *   **Testing:** Designed with testability in mind.\n*   **What is the difference between AngularJS and Angular (2+)?**\n    *   **Answer:** This is a very common question.\n        *   **Language:** AngularJS uses JavaScript, while Angular (2+) uses TypeScript.\n        *   **Architecture:** AngularJS uses MVC, while Angular uses a component-based architecture.\n        *   **Data Binding:** AngularJS uses two-way data binding, while Angular (2+) uses one-way data binding with events for two-way emulation.\n        *   **Mobile Support:** Angular (2+) is designed with mobile-first principles.\n        *   **Performance:** Angular (2+) generally offers better performance.\n        *   **Learning Curve:** Angular (2+) has a steeper learning curve.\n        *   **Dependencies:** Angular utilizes modules, making it more flexible and scalable.\n        *   **Expression Syntax:** Angular utilizes a more simplified expression syntax.\n*   **What is two-way data binding in AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:** Two-way data binding automatically synchronizes the model (data) and the view (UI).  When the model changes, the view is updated, and when the view changes (e.g., user input), the model is updated.  This is achieved using directives like `ng-model`.\n*   **What is Dependency Injection (DI)? How does it work in AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:** DI is a design pattern where an object receives its dependencies from external sources rather than creating them itself.  This promotes loose coupling and testability. In AngularJS:\n        *   Dependencies are declared as arguments to constructors or functions.\n        *   The `$injector` service resolves these dependencies by looking them up in a registry.\n        *   Dependencies can be services, factories, providers, etc.\n*   **What are directives in AngularJS? What are some built-in directives you have used?**\n    *   **Answer:** Directives are markers on DOM elements (attributes, element names, comments, or CSS classes) that tell AngularJS's HTML compiler (`$compile`) to attach a specified behavior to that DOM element or even transform the DOM element and its children.\n\n        *   **Common Built-in Directives:**\n            *   `ng-model`:  Binds an HTML input element to a model property.\n            *   `ng-repeat`:  Repeats a section of HTML for each item in a collection.\n            *   `ng-show`/`ng-hide`:  Shows or hides an element based on an expression.\n            *   `ng-class`:  Dynamically adds or removes CSS classes.\n            *   `ng-click`:  Binds a click event to an expression.\n            *   `ng-src`:  Used for binding image sources (prevents broken image links).\n            *   `ng-href`: Used for binding links.\n            *   `ng-if`: Conditionally adds/removes elements from the DOM.\n\n*   **What are filters in AngularJS? Give some examples.**\n    *   **Answer:** Filters are used to format data for display in the view. They can be applied in templates using the pipe (`|`) character.\n        *   **Examples:**\n            *   `{{ myDate | date:'MM/dd/yyyy' }}`: Formats a date.\n            *   `{{ myNumber | currency }}`: Formats a number as currency.\n            *   `{{ myString | uppercase }}`: Converts a string to uppercase.\n            *   `{{ myString | lowercase }}`: Converts a string to lowercase.\n            *   `{{ myArray | orderBy:'name' }}`: Orders an array by the 'name' property.\n            *   `{{ myString | limitTo:10 }}`: Limits the string to the first 10 characters.\n*   **What are services in AngularJS? How are they different from factories and providers?**\n    *   **Answer:** Services are singleton objects that encapsulate reusable business logic.  They are injected into controllers, directives, and other services.\n\n        *   **Differences:**\n            *   **Service:**  Creates a service by invoking a constructor function with `new`.  You can attach properties and methods to `this` within the constructor.\n            *   **Factory:**  Creates a service by invoking a function that returns an object.  This is the most common way to create services.\n            *   **Provider:**  The most configurable way to create a service.  It allows you to configure the service *before* it's injected into other components.  Providers have a `$get` method that returns the service instance.  This is useful for services that need to be configured based on environment or user settings.\n\n    *   **When to use which:**\n        *   Use `service` when you need a constructor function.\n        *   Use `factory` for most common scenarios where you need to return an object.\n        *   Use `provider` when you need to configure the service before it's used.\n\n*   **What is `$scope`?**\n    *   **Answer:** `$scope` is an object that refers to the application model. It is the glue between the controller and the view. It provides a context for evaluating expressions in the view and allows you to pass data between the controller and the view.  It's organized in a hierarchical structure, with a root scope and child scopes.\n*   **What is the digest cycle in AngularJS? How does it work?**\n    *   **Answer:** The digest cycle is AngularJS's mechanism for updating the view when the model changes.\n        1.  **Trigger:** The digest cycle is triggered by events like user interactions (e.g., clicks, input), AJAX requests, and `$timeout` or `$interval` calls.\n        2.  **`$watch` List:** AngularJS maintains a list of `$watch` expressions.  These expressions are functions that watch for changes in the model.  Directives like `ng-model` automatically create `$watch` expressions.\n        3.  **Evaluation:** During the digest cycle, AngularJS iterates through the `$watch` list and evaluates each expression.\n        4.  **Change Detection:** If an expression's value has changed since the last digest cycle, the corresponding listener function is executed.  This listener function typically updates the DOM.\n        5.  **Looping:** The digest cycle continues to loop until no more changes are detected in the `$watch` expressions.  This ensures that all changes are propagated to the view.\n        6.  **`$apply`:** The `$apply` function is used to execute an expression in AngularJS from outside of the AngularJS framework (e.g., from a third-party library).  It triggers a digest cycle after executing the expression.\n*   **What is the purpose of `$apply()` and `$digest()`?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   `$apply()`:  Used to execute an expression in AngularJS from *outside* the AngularJS framework.  It executes the expression and then triggers a full digest cycle to update the view.  It's necessary because AngularJS doesn't automatically know about changes that happen outside of its own event handlers (e.g., callbacks from `setTimeout`, `addEventListener`).\n        *   `$digest()`:  Manually triggers a digest cycle *within* the current scope. It is rarely used directly, as `$apply()` handles most cases. You might use it if you need to optimize performance by only updating a specific part of the view.\n*   **What is transclusion in directives? When would you use it?**\n    *   **Answer:** Transclusion is a feature that allows a directive to take the content it wraps in the DOM and move it to another location within the directive's template.  It's like creating a \"slot\" where the original content can be inserted.\n    *   **Use cases:**\n        *   Creating reusable components with customizable content.\n        *   Building layout directives where the content needs to be positioned within the layout.\n        *   Creating directives that modify the content while preserving its original functionality.\n*   **What are the different types of directives?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **Element directives:**  Custom HTML elements (e.g., `<my-directive>`).\n        *   **Attribute directives:**  Custom HTML attributes (e.g., `<div my-directive>`).\n        *   **CSS class directives:**  Custom CSS classes (e.g., `<div class=\"my-directive\">`).\n        *   **Comment directives:**  Custom HTML comments (e.g., `<!-- directive: my-directive -->`).\n*   **What is the role of `$http` service?**\n    *   **Answer:** The `$http` service is AngularJS's core service for making HTTP requests to communicate with a server. It provides a simple and convenient way to perform AJAX calls to retrieve data or send data to the server. It returns a promise.\n\n**II. Intermediate Concepts**\n\n*   **How do you create a custom directive?**\n    *   **Answer:**  You use the `.directive()` method on an AngularJS module.  The `.directive()` method takes two arguments: the name of the directive (in camelCase) and a factory function that returns a directive definition object (DDO).\n    ```javascript\n    angular.module('myApp').directive('myDirective', function() {\n      return {\n        restrict: 'E', // Element directive\n        template: '<div>Hello, world!</div>',\n        scope: {}, // Isolated scope (optional)\n        link: function(scope, element, attrs) {\n          // DOM manipulation and event handling here\n        }\n      };\n    });\n    ```\n*   **Explain the different `restrict` options for directives (E, A, C, M).**\n    *   **Answer:** The `restrict` property in a directive definition object specifies how the directive can be used in the HTML.\n        *   `E` (Element): The directive is used as a custom HTML element (e.g., `<my-directive>`).\n        *   `A` (Attribute): The directive is used as an HTML attribute (e.g., `<div my-directive>`).\n        *   `C` (Class): The directive is used as a CSS class (e.g., `<div class=\"my-directive\">`).\n        *   `M` (Comment): The directive is used as an HTML comment (e.g., `<!-- directive: my-directive -->`).\n\n*   **Explain the different `scope` options for directives (false, true, {}).**\n    *   **Answer:** The `scope` property in a directive definition object defines the scope that the directive will use.\n        *   `false` (default): The directive uses the parent scope.  Changes in the directive's scope will affect the parent scope, and vice versa.\n        *   `true`: The directive creates a new child scope that prototypically inherits from the parent scope.  Changes in the directive's scope will not affect the parent scope directly, but changes in the parent scope will be reflected in the directive's scope (unless the directive overrides the property).\n        *   `{}` (isolated scope): The directive creates a completely isolated scope that does not inherit from the parent scope. This is the preferred option for creating reusable components that should not be affected by the parent scope.  You can pass data into the isolated scope using the `scope` property in the directive definition object.\n            *   `@`: (One-way binding - string)  Binds a string value from the parent scope to the directive's scope.  The attribute value is always treated as a string.\n            *   `=`: (Two-way binding - object) Binds an object from the parent scope to the directive's scope.  Changes in the directive's scope will affect the parent scope, and vice versa.\n            *   `&`: (Expression binding) Binds a function from the parent scope to the directive's scope. The directive can then call this function, optionally passing in parameters.\n\n*   **What is the difference between `$watch`, `$watchCollection`, and `$watchGroup`?**\n    *   **Answer:** These are different ways to monitor changes in the model.\n        *   `$watch(watchExpression, listenerExpression, objectEquality)`: Watches a single expression.  The `watchExpression` can be a string (property name) or a function.  The `listenerExpression` is a function that is called when the value of the `watchExpression` changes. The `objectEquality` boolean value will perform a deep watch if set to true.\n        *   `$watchCollection(collection, listener)`: Watches the *elements* of a collection (array or object). It detects when items are added, removed, or moved in the collection.  It does *not* detect changes to the individual elements themselves (for that, you'd still need `$watch`).\n        *   `$watchGroup([watchExpression1, watchExpression2, ...], listener)`: Watches multiple expressions.  The `listener` function is called when any of the expressions change.  The `listener` receives an array of the current values of the expressions and an array of the previous values.\n\n*   **How do you handle events in AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **`ng-click`:**  The most common way to handle click events.\n        *   **Other `ng-*` directives:**  AngularJS provides directives for other common events, such as `ng-mouseover`, `ng-keydown`, `ng-change`, etc.\n        *   **`$event` object:** Within an event handler, you can access the `$event` object, which provides information about the event.\n        *   **Custom directives:** You can create custom directives to handle more complex event scenarios or to encapsulate event handling logic.\n*   **How do you communicate between controllers in AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:** There are several ways to communicate between controllers:\n        *   **Using a shared service:**  This is the most common and recommended approach.  Create a service that holds the data or logic that needs to be shared between the controllers.  Inject the service into both controllers.\n        *   **Using `$rootScope`:** You can store data on the `$rootScope`, which is accessible to all controllers.  However, this should be used sparingly, as it can lead to tight coupling and make it difficult to manage the application state.\n        *   **Using `$emit` and `$broadcast`:** `$emit` dispatches an event upwards through the scope hierarchy, while `$broadcast` dispatches an event downwards through the scope hierarchy.  Controllers can listen for these events using `$on`. This is useful for loosely coupled communication.\n        *   **Using a parent-child relationship:** If one controller is the parent of another (e.g., through nested directives), the child controller can access the parent scope directly (if the directive doesn't use an isolated scope).  However, this approach is generally discouraged as it can lead to tight coupling.\n*   **What are promises in AngularJS? How do you use them with the `$http` service?**\n    *   **Answer:** Promises are objects that represent the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation. They provide a cleaner and more structured way to handle asynchronous code than callbacks.\n    *   **`$http` and Promises:** The `$http` service returns a promise object.  You can use the `.then()`, `.catch()`, and `.finally()` methods on the promise to handle the success, failure, and completion of the HTTP request.\n    ```javascript\n    $http.get('/api/data')\n      .then(function(response) {\n        // Success: Process the response data\n        $scope.data = response.data;\n      })\n      .catch(function(error) {\n        // Error: Handle the error\n        console.error('Error:', error);\n      })\n      .finally(function() {\n        // Completion: Perform any cleanup or final tasks\n        $scope.loading = false;\n      });\n    ```\n*   **What is routing in AngularJS? How do you configure routes?**\n    *   **Answer:** Routing allows you to navigate between different views or sections of a single-page application without reloading the entire page.\n\n    *   **Configuration:**  You use the `$routeProvider` service to configure routes.  The `$routeProvider` is available in the `config` block of an AngularJS module.\n    ```javascript\n    angular.module('myApp').config(function($routeProvider) {\n      $routeProvider\n        .when('/', {\n          templateUrl: 'templates/home.html',\n          controller: 'HomeController'\n        })\n        .when('/about', {\n          templateUrl: 'templates/about.html',\n          controller: 'AboutController'\n        })\n        .otherwise({\n          redirectTo: '/'\n        });\n    });\n    ```\n\n*   **How do you handle errors in AngularJS?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **`$exceptionHandler`:**  You can configure the `$exceptionHandler` service to handle uncaught exceptions in your application.  This allows you to log errors, display error messages to the user, or perform other error-handling tasks.\n        *   **`try...catch` blocks:**  Use `try...catch` blocks to handle exceptions in your code.\n        *   **Promises and `.catch()`:** Use the `.catch()` method on promises to handle errors from asynchronous operations.\n        *   **HTTP interceptors:**  You can use HTTP interceptors to intercept HTTP requests and responses and handle errors that occur during HTTP communication.\n        *   **Custom error handling services:**  Create custom services to encapsulate error-handling logic and make it reusable throughout your application.\n*   **What are HTTP interceptors? How are they used?**\n    *   **Answer:** HTTP interceptors are functions that intercept HTTP requests and responses.  They allow you to modify requests before they are sent to the server and modify responses before they are processed by the application.\n    *   **Use cases:**\n        *   Adding authentication headers to requests.\n        *   Logging HTTP requests and responses.\n        *   Handling errors from HTTP requests.\n        *   Displaying loading indicators while HTTP requests are in progress.\n        *   Transforming request or response data.\n\n**III. Advanced Concepts**\n\n*   **How do you optimize the performance of an AngularJS application?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **Minimize `$watch` expressions:**  The more `$watch` expressions you have, the slower the digest cycle will be.  Avoid unnecessary `$watch` expressions.\n        *   **Use one-time binding (`::`) when possible:**  If a value is not expected to change after it is initially rendered, use one-time binding (`::`) to prevent AngularJS from watching it.\n        *   **Use `track by` in `ng-repeat`:**  When using `ng-repeat` with large collections, use the `track by` expression to help AngularJS efficiently track changes to the collection.  This can significantly improve performance when items are added, removed, or moved in the collection.\n        *   **Use `bindonce` directive (from a third-party library):** The bindonce directive helps to prevent the scope from being watched after it is initially rendered.\n        *   **Debounce or throttle user input:**  If you are watching user input, use debounce or throttle to limit the number of times the digest cycle is triggered.\n        *   **Optimize your data structures:**  Use efficient data structures (e.g., objects instead of arrays for lookups).\n        *   **Use lazy loading:**  Load modules and components only when they are needed.\n        *   **Minimize DOM manipulations:**  DOM manipulations are expensive.  Try to minimize the number of DOM manipulations in your application.\n        *   **Use caching:**  Cache data from the server to reduce the number of HTTP requests.\n        *   **Use server-side rendering (SSR):**  SSR can improve the initial load time of your application, especially for search engine optimization (SEO).\n        *   **Profile your code:**  Use the AngularJS Batarang browser extension or other profiling tools to identify performance bottlenecks in your code.\n*   **What is the purpose of the `$compile` service?**\n    *   **Answer:** The `$compile` service is responsible for processing the HTML in your AngularJS application and converting it into a live, interactive DOM.  It traverses the DOM, finds directives, and attaches the corresponding behavior to the DOM elements. It essentially transforms the static HTML into dynamic, AngularJS-aware elements.\n\n*   **How does AngularJS handle security? What are some common security vulnerabilities and how can you prevent them?**\n    *   **Answer:** AngularJS has some built-in security features, but it's important to be aware of potential vulnerabilities and take steps to mitigate them.\n        *   **Cross-Site Scripting (XSS):**\n            *   **Vulnerability:** XSS attacks occur when malicious code is injected into your application and executed by users.\n            *   **Prevention:**\n                *   **Input validation:**  Validate all user input on the server-side.\n                *   **Output encoding:**  Encode data before displaying it in the view to prevent it from being interpreted as HTML or JavaScript.  AngularJS automatically encodes data by default, but you should be aware of situations where you might need to explicitly encode data (e.g., when rendering HTML from a trusted source). Use `$sce` to whitelist trusted URLs.\n        *   **Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF):**\n            *   **Vulnerability:** CSRF attacks occur when an attacker tricks a user into performing an action on your application without their knowledge.\n            *   **Prevention:**\n                *   **CSRF tokens:**  Include a CSRF token in your forms and AJAX requests.  The server should verify the token before processing the request.\n        *   **Server-Side Security:**\n            *   **Vulnerability:** AngularJS is a front-end framework, so it's crucial to secure your server-side code as well.\n            *   **Prevention:**\n                *   **Authentication:**  Implement proper authentication to verify the identity of users.\n                *   **Authorization:**  Implement proper authorization to restrict access to resources based on user roles.\n        *   **Dependencies:**\n            *   **Vulnerability:** Using outdated versions of libraries can introduce security vulnerabilities.\n            *   **Prevention:**\n                *   Keep dependencies updated to the latest versions.\n        *   **`$sce` (Strict Contextual Escaping):**\n            *   **Vulnerability:**  Allows for the injection of untrusted HTML, CSS, or JavaScript.\n            *   **Prevention:**\n                *   Use `$sce` to whitelist trusted URLs and HTML snippets.  Avoid using `$sce.trustAsHtml` unless you are absolutely sure that the data is safe.\n*   **Explain the concept of lazy loading in AngularJS. How do you implement it?**\n    *   **Answer:** Lazy loading is a technique where you load modules or components only when they are needed, rather than loading them all at once when the application starts. This can improve the initial load time of your application and reduce the amount of memory it consumes.\n\n    *   **Implementation:**\n        *   **`ocLazyLoad`:**  A popular third-party library for lazy loading modules and components in AngularJS. It provides a simple API for loading modules on demand.\n\n*   **What are the benefits of using AngularJS with TypeScript?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **Static typing:** TypeScript adds static typing to JavaScript, which can help you catch errors earlier in the development process.\n        *   **Improved code organization:** TypeScript encourages you to write more organized and maintainable code.\n        *   **Better tooling:** TypeScript has better tooling support than JavaScript, including autocompletion, refactoring, and debugging.\n        *   **Easier to learn Angular (2+):** If you are planning to migrate to Angular (2+), learning TypeScript will make the transition easier.\n\n**IV. Testing**\n\n*   **How do you test AngularJS applications?**\n    *   **Answer:**\n        *   **Unit testing:** Test individual components (controllers, services, directives) in isolation.  Use a testing framework like Jasmine or Mocha, and a mocking library like Sinon.js.\n        *   **End-to-end (E2E) testing:** Test the entire application from end to end, simulating user interactions.  Use a testing framework like Protractor (specifically designed for AngularJS).\n        *   **Karma:**  A test runner that executes your tests in a browser environment.\n*   **What is the purpose of using mocks in unit tests?**\n    *   **Answer:** Mocks are used to replace dependencies in unit tests.  This allows you to isolate the component that you are testing and prevent external dependencies from affecting the test results.  Mocks also allow you to control the behavior of dependencies and simulate different scenarios.\n*   **How do you use Protractor for E2E testing?**\n    *   **Answer:** Protractor is an end-to-end testing framework specifically designed for AngularJS applications. It uses WebDriver to interact with the browser and simulate user interactions.\n    ```javascript\n    // Example Protractor test\n    describe('My AngularJS App', function() {\n      it('should have a title', function() {\n        browser.get('http://localhost:8000');\n        expect(browser.getTitle()).toEqual('My App');\n      });\n    });\n    ```\n\n**V.  Scenario-Based Questions**\n\n*   \"Describe a time when you had to debug a difficult AngularJS issue. What was the issue, and how did you resolve it?\"\n*   \"How would you implement a directive that displays a list of items and allows the user to filter the list based on a search term?\"\n*   \"How would you handle authentication in an AngularJS application that uses a REST API?\"\n*   \"How would you implement a service that caches data from the server and invalidates the cache when the data is updated?\"\n*   \"Imagine you have a large AngularJS application with many controllers and services. How would you structure the application to make it more maintainable and scalable?\"\n\n**Tips for Answering**\n\n*   **Be clear and concise:**  Get to the point quickly and avoid rambling.\n*   **Use technical terminology correctly:** Show that you understand the concepts.\n*   **Provide examples:** Illustrate your answers with code snippets or real-world examples.\n*   **Explain your reasoning:** Don't just state facts; explain why things work the way they do.\n*   **Be honest about your experience:** If you don't know the answer to a question, it's better to say so than to try to fake it.  You can say, \"I haven't used that specifically, but I'm familiar with the general concept of...\"\n*   **Ask clarifying questions:** If you're not sure what the interviewer is asking, ask for clarification.\n*   **Show enthusiasm:** Express your interest in AngularJS and your passion for web development.\n*   **Prepare:**  Review the core concepts, practice answering questions out loud, and think about examples from your past projects.\n\nGood luck with your interview!  Remember to tailor your answers to your own experience and the specific requirements of the job.\n",
